One day before closing and this is my first prediction on this question. USD/CHN stands right around 6.568. The exchange rate hasn't been below 6.3 since its big three day run up in August. Since then the RMB's biggest daily rise was from about 6.47 to a around 6.385 in early September. A quick scouring of the charts shows an average trading day movement since then has been less than a third of that open to close. There has been virtually no movement on any period from late afternoon on Fridays (EST) to Sunday afternoons (EST). Given that it is now 15:25 EST on a Friday there is little reason to think there will be much movement in the next day.

Today is my first forecast for this question - I am late to the game. The current exchange rate is 6.4807 (Dec 21). In 10 days, I am estimating that there is only a 11% chance it falls below 6.40. This is based on the (very) few things I know about the yuan / USD exchange rate, namely: (1) The yuan is a "managed float" currency. The exchange rate is largely controlled by the Chinese government, and is under-going a managed devaluation to stimulate export growth due to a weakening economy. (2) On Nov 30, the yuan entered the IMF's selective basket of reserve currencies, and the Chinese government has vowed to keep the yuan stable So the question becomes: What is the likelihood of the government to reverse the current devaluation strategy, in the next 10 days, so that the exchange rate falls below 6.40 USD? Frankly, if all my assumptions are right, then it will be even more unlikely than I have estimated here. However, there's still a lot I don't know on this topic, so I've left room to allow for my ignorance.

In the last month the renminbi has been increasing it's value from 6.37 to 6.46. in 2015 (even including the surge in August) it has remained between 6.2 and today's maximum. And looking at the last 5 years, it has oscillated between 6.06 and 6.66. This shows that the volatility of the renminbi has been relatively low - at least compared with other currencies, such as the Mexican Peso for instance that has experienced much bigger changes. This despite significant manipulation from both the Chinese and US governments over their currencies.

With just over a month left until January, it's unlikely that market forces will push this ratio down by as much as 0.1 over this period of time, ie to 6.30. The preponderance of forces - Chinese monetary policy, the state of the US dollar - are creating an upward pressure on the short term. A new year's announcement by the Chinese government on the morning of Jan. 1 - a sudden devaluation for instance - could cause a rapid change in value, most likely upward as in August. A sudden drop would probably require a sudden fall in US or world financial markets which is probably unlikely on Jan. 1 when most traders will still be taking their hangover cures. But then, what with Black Swans and automated trading, who knows?

FOREX predictions are often a tale of tears, but there will almost certainly not be any dramatic change in the dollar-renminbi exchange rate by this date. The renminbi doesn't float freely. In recent times, it would hardly change at all over the course of a year. The exchange rate is manipulated by the Chinese government officials for three contradictory purposes. (1) They want an undervalued currency to promote exports. (2) They aspire to have the renminbi become a reserve currency in the future. (3) They have an internal political imperative to preserve the belief that they have absolute control over everything. Recent information now suggests that the ECB will pursue a looser monetary policy, putting downward pressure on the Euro over time. This will mess up Chinese goal #1 and create pressure for another Chinese devaluation. However, the most recent devaluation episode made them lose face with respect to goals #2 and #3. They also have a potentially dangerous political showdown coming up regarding territorial claims in the South China Sea. They won't want to show weakness with respect to the exchange rate while they are playing the bully role with respect to the first island chain. The only problem here is that 6.36 is on the bubble between two artificial choices. The correct answer is somewhat more likely to be (C) than (B) since that would favor Chinese goal #1
